LASSA FEVER - WEST AFRICA (29): NIGERIA
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1] National
[2] Niger state, suspected

******
[1] National
Date: Sun 27 May 2018
Source: Nigeria Centre for Disease Control [edited]
http://www.oie.int/wahis_2/public/wahid.php/Reviewreport/Review?page_refer=MapFullEventReport&reportid=26716


Highlights
- In the reporting week 21 (21-27 May 2018) no new confirmed case was reported.
- From 1 Jan - 27 May 2018, a total of 1968 suspected cases have been reported from 21 states. Of these, 431 were confirmed positive, 10 are probable, 1523 negative (not a case) and 4 samples are awaiting laboratory results (pending).
- Since the onset of the 2018 outbreak, there have been 108 deaths in confirmed cases and 10 in probable cases. Case fatality rate in confirmed cases is 25.1 percent -Table 1.
- 21 states have recorded at least one confirmed case across 71 Local Government Areas (Edo, Ondo, Bauchi, Nasarawa, Ebonyi, Anambra, Benue, Kogi, Imo, Plateau, Lagos, Taraba, Delta, Osun, Rivers, FCT, Gombe, Ekiti, Kaduna, Abia and Adamawa); 16 states have exited the active phase of the outbreak while 5 -- Edo, Ondo, Ebonyi, Taraba and Adamawa States -- remain active; Table 1/ Figure 1.
- In the reporting week 21, no new healthcare worker was infected; 38 health care workers have been affected since the onset of the outbreak in 8 states: Ebonyi (16), Edo (12), Ondo (4), Kogi (2), Benue (1), Nasarawa (1), Taraba (1), and Abia (1) with 9 deaths in Ebonyi (6), Kogi (1), Abia (1) and Ondo (1).
- Age-group 21-40 years is predominantly affected (median age is 32 years); Figure 6.
- The male to female ratio for confirmed cases is 1.6:1.
- 81 percent of all confirmed cases are from Edo (42 percent), Ondo (24 percent) and Ebonyi (15 percent) states.
- One case is currently being managed at Adamawa State treatment Centre; Table 1.
- A total of 5327 contacts have been identified from 21 states. Of these 55 (1.0 percent) are currently being followed up; 5261 (98.8 percent) have completed 21 days follow up, while 11 (0.2 percent) were lost to follow up. 82 symptomatic contacts have been identified, of which 28 (36 percent) have tested positive from 5 states (Edo-13, Ondo-8, Ebonyi-3, Kogi-3 and Bauchi-1); Table 1.
- The National Lassa fever After Action Review Meeting (AARM) is scheduled for 5-7 Jun 2018.
- The National intensive clinical workshop on diagnosis, management and control of Lassa fever in collaboration with ISTH Northeast/Northwest zones is scheduled for 12-14 Jun 2018.
- Lassa fever multi-partner, multi-agency Technical Working Group (TWG) continues to coordinate response activities at all levels.

